<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1526,1658]" pageId="2" pageNumber="375">
The genus is widely distributed. Most species occur in the Palearctic Region, but some can be found also in the Nearctic, Neotropical, Afrotropical, Oriental and Australian Regions (
<bibRefCitation box="[1005,1179,1562,1587]" pageId="2" pageNumber="375" refId="ref9615" refString="Ackland, D. M. (2001) Revision of afrotropical Anthomyia Meigen, 1803 (Diptera: Anthomyiidae), with descriptions of ten new species. African Invertebrates, 42, 1 - 94." type="journal article">Ackland 2001</bibRefCitation>
). This is the largest anthomyiid genus in the Neotropical Region with 16 species described (
<bibRefCitation box="[985,1202,1598,1623]" pageId="2" pageNumber="375" refId="ref9653" refString="Albuquerque, D. de O. (1958) Uma nova especie de &quot; Hylemyioides &quot; Albuquerque, 1949 (Diptera, Muscidae, Anthomyinae). Revista Brasileira de Biologia, 18, 341 - 344." type="journal article">Albuquerque 1958</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[1216,1431,1598,1623]" pageId="2" pageNumber="375" refId="ref9692" refString="Albuquerque, D. de O. (1959) Contribuicao ao conhecimento de Pegomyia R. - D., 1930 e Hylemyia (Craspedochaeta) Macquart, 1850, na America do Sul, com descricoes de especies novas (Diptera-Muscidae). Boletim do Museu Nacional, Nova Serie, Zoologia, 210, 12 - 50." type="journal article">Albuquerque 1959</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[151,269,1634,1658]" pageId="2" pageNumber="375" refId="ref11124" refString="Pont, A. C. (1974) Family Anthomyiidae. In: Papavero, N. (Ed.), A catalogue of the Diptera of the Americas South of the United States. Departamento de Zoologia, Universidade de Sao Paulo, Sao Paulo, pp. 1 - 21." type="book chapter">Pont 1974</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
